@Blurhy: I found it.
So apparently the current implementation of the regex engine that zeronet uses(`ZeroBundle/lib/Python2.7/re.py`) is broken, since `re.match("^([^/]*)/(.*)$", "1Something/content.json")` just returns `none`, where as `re.match("^([^/]*)/(.*)$", "1Something/SomethingElse/content.json")` returns the expected regex groups of `1Something` and `SomethingElse/content.json`. Doing the same in an `python2.7.15`, `python2.7.11` or `python3.7.2` console works as expected, which is weird because the `python2.7.11 re.py __version__ ` was 2.2.1, the exact same version as the one in `ZeroBundle/lib/Python2.7/re.py`.

The reason why the hub-content.json didn't show up is because it actually did, but when gathering the `directory, file_name` in `Db.py`(line 306) `re.match(...)` returned `none` and trying to call `groups()` on a `none` object threw an exception which caused the `1SomeHub/content.json` to be ignored when building the database.

